Hello,

Consider the following:

```
function customizer(objValue, srcValue) {
  var ret;
  if (_.isObject(objValue) && _.isObject(srcValue)) {
    ret = undefined; // recurse by default
  } else {
    ret = objValue===undefined || (srcValue!==undefined && srcValue!==null) ? srcValue : objValue;
  }
  return ret;
}

var obj = {
  o1: null,
  o2: null
};
var orig_obj = _.clone(obj);
var def = {
  t1: undefined,
  t2: undefined,
  t3: undefined,
  t4: null,
  t5: null,
  t6: null,
  t7: "7",
  t8: "8",
  t9: 9,
  t10: obj // reference to obj!
};
var orig_def = _.cloneDeep(def);
```

Note the reference to `obj` in `def` object, at `t10` key.
Now, some object that contains values to be merged with `def`.

```
var row = {
  t1: undefined,
  t2: null,
  t3: "t3",
  t4: undefined,
  t5: null,
  t6: 6,
  t7: undefined,
  t8: null,
  t9: "9",
  t10: {
    o1: "a"
  }
};
```

Below is the expected value of merge with customizer:

```
var ex = {
  t2: null,
  t3: "t3",
  t4: null,
  t5: null,
  t6: 6,
  t7: "7",
  t8: "8",
  t9: "9",
  t10: {
    o1: "a",
    o2: null
  }
};
```

If we merge with noop, then the sources are untouched. Of course, the expected value is not what was intended, but that's not the issue here.

```
var x1 = _.mergeWith({}, def, row, _.noop);
console.log("x1 --> ", x1);
console.log("x1 == ex --> ", _.isEqual(x1, ex)); // false as expected
console.log("def == orig_def --> ", _.isEqual(def, orig_def)); // true as expected
console.log("obj == orig_obj --> ", _.isEqual(obj, orig_obj)); // true as expected
console.log("obj --> ", obj);
/*
obj is, as expected:
  {
    o1: null,
    o2: null
  }
*/
```

However, if we merge with customizer, then the sources are modified.

```
var x2 = _.mergeWith({}, def, row, customizer);
console.log("x2 --> ", x2);
console.log("x2 == ex --> ", _.isEqual(x2, ex)); // true as expected
console.log("def == orig_def --> ", _.isEqual(def, orig_def)); // FALSE!
console.log("obj == orig_obj --> ", _.isEqual(obj, orig_obj)); // FALSE!
console.log("obj --> ", obj);
/*
obj is MODIFIED:
  {
    o1: "a",
    o2: null
  }
*/
```

I don't know if this is the intended behavior, I solved the issue passing to original `t10` key a cloned object, but it looks like an inconsistence in `mergeWith` behavior, compared with `merge` (which does not modify the sources).

Thank you

Recently I've encountered an issue where [adding fractional numbers results in rounding errors](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/588004/is-floating-point-math-broken). This can be solved by using a rounding implementation (lodash' _.round seems to be a proper implementation, but there's some controversy around rounding in javascript and people tend to resort to the manual [Firefox rounding implementation](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Math/round#Decimal_rounding)).

Case in point:

``` javascript
var a = 14.38;
var b = 148.95;
var c = a + b;

console.log(c); // 163.32999999999998
console.log(_.round(c, 2)); // 163.33

// similar error with 0.1 + 0.2 and so on
```

Normally we can compensate for these rounding errors by rounding after the addition. _.sum doesn't support this: given enough numbers to summate the result _.sum gives forces us to reduce the decimals we must round to, in order to eliminate the rounding error.

I've prepare a jsFiddle with an example. https://jsfiddle.net/plantface/f0h2rj5a/

All the `_.union` family of functions are chainable, but don't actually work when used in a chain. The problem is that  `union()` takes multiple array arguments instead of a collection of arrays, but the whole chained value is passed as the first argument without being split. So this happens:

``` js
// Use u instead of _ in the repl
u([[1,2,3,5],[1,2,4,8]]).union().value();
// [ [ 1, 2, 3, 5 ], [ 1, 2, 4, 8 ] ]
u([[1,2,3,5],[1,2,4,8]]).unionBy(u.identity).value();
// [ [ 1, 2, 3, 5 ], [ 1, 2, 4, 8 ] ]
u([[1,2,3,5],[1,2,4,8]]).unionBy('a').value();
// [ [ 1, 2, 3, 5 ] ]  both == 'undefined'
```

This was referenced in https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/1105 and the solution was to just use `_.spread`, which only really works for plain `_.union` but more importantly defeats the point of `_.union` being chainable at all. 

Right now, the behavior of `union()` in a chain is the same as `uniq()`:

``` js
u([1,2,2,3,23]).union().value();
// [ 1, 2, 3, 23 ]
```

It's doubtful that anyone is using it this way intentionally. 

I would either not make `_.union` and its buddies chainable at all, or automatically `spread()` when union is invoked on a chain.

Let me know what you think, I'll happily make a PR.

Hi! First of all, thanks for this amazing project. Now to the request, it would be really nice if we could return a default value if the `find` method doesn't find anything.

Simple use case:

Let's say we have to return the age of the first person with name 'Mateo'. Normally we would need to do it like this:

``` javascript
let people = _([
  { name: 'Adam', age: 27 },
  { name: 'Jane', age: 24 },
  { name: 'David', age: 26 },
  { name: 'Jeffrey', age: 32 },
  { name: 'Evan', age: 26 },
]);

let person = people.find({ name: 'Mateo' });

if (person) {
  return person.age;
}

return 0;
```

But wouldn't it be nicer if could just simply do this:

``` javascript
return people
         .find({ name: 'Mateo' }, 0, { name: ' ', age: 0 })
         .age;
```

This gets even more relevant when you start to use `Null Objects` with it's own methods. It saves the check to see if something was found.

